        abstract: "The paper proposes a triangulation of potential artistic approaches to working critically with, through, and on generative AI (GenAI), resulting in three coordinates: <em>AI imaginaries</em> – practices of conceiving and creating imagery through GenAI applications, as well as imaginaries about the limitations and potentials of AI in general; <em>AI deconstructions</em> – studies of the effects and affects fostered by GenAI and the relation to the technology’s cultural history, including the deconstruction of the technology itself; <em>AI exposures</em> – investigations into the technological and systemic conditions of GenAI and its implications for dispositifs of power and control.<br><br>The paper discusses the viability of this triangulation as a framework for the analysis of artistic practices engaging with GenAI, be it on the level of tools assisting in the creation of the work, or as research object the work critically engages with. The framework challenges the assumption that AI generators merely reproduce characteristics inherently present in the underlying datasets. Instead, it provokes us to investigate the question of how aesthetic practices may critically engage with GenAI. The paper is based on insights developed in a research seminar organized at the University of Copenhagen’s Department for Arts and Cultural Studies which hosted artists and researchers investigating GenAI.",
