        abstract: "Oxford's word of the year for 2024, <em>brain rot</em>, or <em>putrefazione cerebrale</em>, as the late Pope Francis put it, refers to online content, expressions, concepts, and behaviours that are believed to have negative psychological and cognitive consequences for users or are themselves the result of such phenomena. In early 2025, a new phenomenon, created by artificial intelligence, called Italian brainrot emerged on social media and in meme culture centred around nonsensical images of animals with equally nonsensical, Italian-sounding names. Countless short videos created an absurd and chaotic mythology around them, resulting in a kind of ironically manic (and manically ironic) collective online hallucination, in which the entire internet identified with enjoying an almost hypnotic nonsense. Basically, it was shitposting taken to the extreme, but for the first time, artificial intelligence played a central role. In this talk, I will show why the phenomenon of Italian brainrot was made possible precisely because the images were AI-generated, and I will attempt to outline what this may mean for the future influence of artificial intelligence on the aesthetics of the internet.",
