        abstract: "Generative artificial intelligence is already being incorporated extensively in all steps of audiovisual media production: data driven scripts, generation of images, audio and video, postproduction, using LLM models for media distribution and other stages. While there is no universally accepted framework of automation applied specifically to audiovisual production, some scholars have used the automation framework for self-driving cars as a basis of distinguishing the different levels of automation in audiovisual media. And while full automation is highly unlikely to be achieved anytime soon, as generative AI tools are progressing rapidly on a daily basis, I question the impact of highly automated processes of audiovisual production on creativity, labour, culture and the perception of reality. Using various theories of automation, creativity, audiovisual production and culture, I will attempt to assess the current state and possible future development of automated audiovisual media.",
        bio: "<strong>NIKOLAJ FIŠER</strong> is a Junior Researcher at the Faculty of Arts, University of Ljubljana (Sociology of Culture) and a PhD student at Universitat Autònoma de Barcelona (audiovisual communication). He has presented at ECREA (2023, 2024) and NODOS (2024), with publications in PLOS ONE, a book chapter in NODOS proceedings, and a forthcoming paper in <em>Ars et Humanitas</em>."
