        title: "The object of technics in the surrounding world",
        abstract: "In this presentation, I propose an extension and reworking of Simondon's concept of the techno-geographical milieu through a synthesis of Gibson's concept of the affordance and Wittgenstein's language games. The agent's surrounding world is primarily constituted by affordances, i.e., various possibilities of action, which include both “mental” acts and all others. I certainly argue that there is no privileged status of thought, or rather, I follow Wittgenstein, who writes in the <em>Blue book</em> that the place where thinking takes place is the point of contact between pen and paper—here I also refer to the concept of the operational chain and Leroi-Gourhan. The system of points of reference conditions every intentional content, which gives it a structural place similar to Aristotle's or Kant's system of categories, but with a different origin; points of reference are a matter of rules or habits and, as such, are culturally mediated. In this way, I can point out that the phenomena we usually call “technics” and cultural life are primarily distinguished by their social consequences, because every action is in itself a technology. In conclusion, I suggest that such a supplement to the techno-geographical milieu allows us to think of techniques not as opposed to humans, but as a scene of antagonism and alienation.",
        bio: "<strong>MATIJA PUŠNIK</strong>, MA in Philosophy, primarily deals with the use of debate and argumentation pedagogy as a tool for the development of critical thinking and various forms of literacy (with an emphasis on media, information, and data literacy) in formal and informal education. He is employed as head of education at IDEA (International Debate Education Association) and has previously written for Radio Študent and Disenz."
