        title: "New forms and new theories of intelligence: /the earthbound visual cultures/",
        abstract: "By the end of the 20th century, image processing and machine vision had successfully operationalised the theory of visual culture. From that point on, the gaze re-emerges as a product of socio-economic efforts that has been successfully converted into a stream of data, which is then mediated, parsed and reassembled within the framework of computational AI systems.<br><br>The fact that AI can relate to the external environment through complex statistical models is a fascinating technical achievement in itself. Similarly fascinating is the idea of placing algorithms at the heart of current aesthetic and political debates. So why should it be any different?<br><br>I believe a counter-position to this approach results from the study of technological principles. In my talk, I will argue that AI technologies have a surprisingly concrete, non-computational facet. The strength of visual techniques derives from their multiplicity and the various ways in which they can be linked to external entities. Recognising this variety is key to the study of AI vision, which takes up the mantle of debating how presupposed purely algorithmic systems resonate with their nearest surroundings.<br><br>I will emphasise the importance of carefully observing the environments that have emerged in relation to the development of contemporary vision technologies. In doing so, I link machine vision to collectives that work primarily with coarse-grained matter rather than computational tasks. I argue for research that, instead of insisting on technologies in terms of cloud-based computing, turns towards terrestrial phenomena reworked on the basis of photometry, visual communication design, and the geophysical study of ecosystems. The idea is to consider vision as an earthbound phenomenon that persistently evades confinement within computational systems.",
